i\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Peritubal cysts","Paratubal cysts","Hydrosalpinx","Pyosalpinx","Haematosalpinx"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe specimen shows classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydrosalpinx\u003C/strong\u003E, which is characterized by a pathologically dilated fallopian tube filled with clear, serous fluid. The condition typically develops as a late complication of pelvic inflammatory disease, where scarring leads to distal tubal obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeritubal cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are fluid-filled structures located around the fallopian tube but not within it. \u003Cstrong\u003EParatubal cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are remnants of the mesonephric or paramesonephric ducts and appear as separate structures from the fallopian tube. \u003Cstrong\u003EPyosalpinx\u003C/strong\u003E contains purulent material rather than clear fluid and is associated with acute inflammation. \u003Cstrong\u003EHaematosalpinx\u003C/strong\u003E contains blood and is typically associated with ectopic pregnancy or endometriosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hydrosalpinx appears as a fluid-filled, dilated fallopian tube with thin walls and loss of mucosal folds.","Hydrosalpinx is a late consequence of pelvic inflammatory disease causing tubal obstruction."],"references":["Parihar M, Mirge A, Hasabe R. Hydrosalpinx functional surgery or salpingectomy? The importance of hydrosalpinx fluid in assisted reproductive technologies. J Gynecol Endosc Surg. 2009 Jan;1(1):12-6. doi: 10.4103/0974-1216.51903. PMID: 22442504; PMCID: PMC3304258.","Dey M, Kumar R. Isolated torsion of hydrosalpinx. Med J Armed Forces India. 2013 Apr;69(2):178-80. doi: 10.1016/j.mjafi.2012.04.016. Epub 2012 Sep 14. PMID: 24600095; PMCID: PMC3862943.","El-Kharoubi AF. Tubal Pathologies and Fertility Outcomes: A Review. Cureus. 2023 May 11;15(5):e38881. doi: 10.7759/cureus.38881. PMID: 37197301; PMCID: PMC10184952.","Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47746"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15710"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47746"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-17T16:48:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-17T16:48:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8401"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62299"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","n